# Global Rules

## Identity
- Never mention Claude, Claude Code, or AI in any commit, PR, comment, or message
- Commits: short, lowercase, no fluff. e.g. `fix auth redirect on logout`. No `Co-Authored-By`
- PRs: human-written tone, brief explanation of what/why. No templates, no checklists, no AI footer

## Code Style
- Immutability: always create new objects, never mutate existing ones
- Files: 200-400 lines typical, 800 max. Organize by feature/domain
- Functions: <50 lines. No deep nesting (>4 levels)
- Validate all input at system boundaries. Never silently swallow errors
- Run linter/formatter before every commit (ruff for Python, biome for JS/TS, gofumpt for Go, cargo fmt for Rust)

## Workflow
1. Research first (`/search-first`, context7)
2. Plan (`/plan`) before non-trivial work (>2 files or >1 hour)
3. TDD (`/tdd`) — tests first, 80%+ coverage
4. Review (`/code-review`) before merge
5. Security review (`/security-review`) for auth, billing, API, infra
6. Verify (`/verify`) before claiming done

## Security
- No hardcoded secrets — env vars or secret managers only
- Parameterized queries only. Validate all inputs. Rate limit public endpoints
- Never leak stack traces or internal paths to clients
- Run `/security-scan` before commits touching auth/billing/API

## Git
Commit format: `<type>: <description>` (feat, fix, refactor, docs, test, chore, perf, ci)

## Model Routing
- Default for web research/exploration/file search agents: `model: "haiku"`
- User can override per-task: "use sonnet for this research" or "use opus for this"
- Code implementation, review, security, architecture agents: always inherit session model
- Use `/effort low` for trivial tasks, `/effort high` only for complex work

## RTK (Rust Token Killer)
**Always prefix Bash commands with `rtk`** for 60-90% token savings on output. RTK passes through unchanged if no filter exists — always safe to use. In chains: `rtk git add . && rtk git commit -m "msg"`. Use `rtk gain` to check savings stats.

## Code Graph (codebase-memory-mcp)
**ALWAYS query the knowledge graph BEFORE using Grep/Glob/Read.** Use `search_code` for code search, `trace_path` for impact analysis, `get_architecture` for codebase overview. Say "index this project" to build the graph. Fall back to file tools only when graph doesn't cover it.

## Code Connectivity (CRITICAL — the #1 AI failure mode)
- BEFORE writing a new file: identify WHERE it will be imported. Name the file and line
- NEVER write a file without immediately wiring it into the system
- After creating ANY new module/function/component, show WHERE it's imported and called
- After creating ANY new endpoint, show the router registration line
- After creating ANY new component, show the parent that renders it
- Use `find_referencing_symbols` (serena MCP) or `trace_path` (codebase-memory) to verify connectivity
- If new code has zero callers = NOT DONE. Wire it up or delete it
- Before claiming done, show this trace:
  ENTRY: [main/router/CLI] -> ROUTE -> HANDLER -> SERVICE -> STORAGE
  TEST: [test name exercising this chain]
  RESULT: [actual test output, not "should work"]

## Testing (REAL tests, not theater)
- Integration tests > unit tests. Test the RUNNING system, not mocked fantasies
- Max 2 mocks per test. Never mock the system under test itself
- Every test must have behavioral assertions — not `toBeTruthy()` or `toBe(x)` where x is the input
- Write the FAILING integration test FIRST, then implement to make it pass
- Tests must fail if the feature is removed — if they still pass, the test is fake
- For APIs: test with real HTTP (supertest/reqwest/httptest), not mocked handlers
- For DB: use real schema (testcontainers/migrations), not in-memory fakes

## Verification (NEVER skip)
- Run tests and show output before marking ANY task complete
- Run type checker (pyright/tsc/cargo check) and show 0 errors
- NEVER say "this should work" — prove it does with evidence
- For bug fixes: show the original error no longer occurs
- Use LSP tools (getDiagnostics, goToDefinition, findReferences) over Grep for code navigation

## Token Efficiency
- `/clear` between unrelated tasks. `/compact` at logical breakpoints
- Use Explore agent or smart_search/smart_outline instead of reading entire files
- Prefer CLI tools (gh, aws) over MCP equivalents when possible
